column2: I would advocate for the Cranbourne Dandenong line duplication. Our train stations are packed at Merrinda and Cranbourne, there are not enough parking spaces and our trains get often terminated at Dandenong. For those working in the city the travel times can take up to two ours and this creates a lot of frustration. In one word commuting to the City and back is a nightmare. When we are coming back from work we want to get back to our families earlier and not having a reliable transport ads additional stress in our lives. The population in the area has grown considerably in the last few years and the need for the duplication between Dandenong and Cranbourne should be considered as an URGENCY. We are paying our taxes, we are paying for the fares but we are not getting any value for the money we are paying.

I am a support worker in the adult mental health sector and I would like to see more services and help available for people with mental illness. The system is overstretched, and only 10 per cent of our current clients will be eligible for the NDIS when it comes out in 2019. People can't afford the gap fees to see psychologists. We have almost 100 people on our waiting list for services at the moment, these people won't get any help for at least a year. I would like to see Council take a leading role in advocating for more support for people with mental health problems as I fear that we will have serious problems for the community if we don't do more now.

I would like Casey to be a safe and productive where technology is common rather than a struggle. 
However, in the last 3 years Casey is nothing of this type. Most people are scared in their homes because they don't know when someone they do not know will enter even if they don't wish them to. Further, since we've lived here - over 15 years now - our internet connection has only gotten worse and not better. Then when we thought we were going to be joining at least the 21st century with our connection, we have now gotten shuffled off the list and we're stuck with an internet connection which you can barely use and forget any kind of streaming service. In order to be a productive and technology updated area, Casey (Springvale ward) isn't even able to cope in 2016, so I doubt by 2041 things will change.
column2:
This is a hard question to answer as there is so much in Casey that needs to be looked at - traffic congestion, employment, computer connections, safety, and a council and MP who cares for the entire area and not just areas where they are worried about not getting votes. 
According to the overall question, if I had to pick just one area I am the most concerned with it would be how the current council and state MP centre on areas where they do not think they will not get votes to get back into office. Further, to hold as many closed door meetings as this council does, according to the minutes of the council that I have been reading, each session has a lengthy section of time during each meeting which is closed and away from the public. To me, as a ratepayer, I feel that we should not have things that are hidden away like dirty laundry. It should be a transparent council where the public and people who pay your wages know what is going on instead of getting closed meetings.

column1: One powered  by 100% renewable energy for a start! Fully integrated public transport system with links to transcontinental HSR. Better traffic management systems to better assist fully-autonomous vehicles (then at 50%+ private ownership and rising fast). Greater levels of environmental protection on all accounts. By then we would have eliminated urban sprawl and be concentrating on densifying existing developed areas of all types. Better and improved access to public green space and an established public footway & cycleway network spanning the Shire & beyond. We would have also completed the NBN many years ago and be investing in photonic-switch systems allowing even greater speed & higher bandwidth. Also be then we will have completely eliminated all landfill waste through a variety of programs and incentives. Storm water systems will have been up-graded to cope with the worst a post anthropogenic climate change environment can dish out, including but not limited to the removal of any pollutants found in the water prior to discharge into watercourses. There's more but I think that's a good start :-)
column2: Massive & sustained investment in renewable power systems both in terms of production & distribution across the Shire and beyond.

column1:
FUTURE RESIDENT
Paul and Paula
I think the opportunity to have amenity and work opportunities within the municipality. Idea of having to travel out of town is dreadful. Encouraging businesses that employ others in the community would be valuable. Big believer in the value of having attractive places/areas. Parks encourage people to get out and meet each other. Travelling libraries  once a week or month would help for people who dont have cars

What attracted you to Casey? 

The Mariot waters estate. I dont drive and I can walk to the shops and it is close to my daughter who has just had a baby.
As we are maturing in age it is good as it is not too hilly and the Mariot water estate is fairly flat. Opposite a council park. Keen for council to put some amenities.
column2:
FUTURE RESIDENT
When you were looking to move, did you have any concerns about Casey? Or things that you thought might be missing?
Concern about public transport  buses. Im in business and engage with chamber of commerce in Dandenong. I would be interested in joining the chamber there. There needs to be better connected public transport. Footpaths  along Thompsons road need to be upgraded  really dangerous at the moment.
Safety and security  is paramount. Council should support neighbourhood watch. Lighting and security cameras.
